          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which gene on the Y chromosome acts as the master switch for male sex determinat</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which gene on the Y chromosome acts as the master switch for male sex determination in the human embryo?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>AMH gene</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Anti-Müllerian hormone is produced by Sertoli cells of the already-formed testis to regress the Müllerian ducts — it acts downstream of SRY, not as the initiating switch.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>SRY gene</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The SRY (Sex-determining Region Y) protein is expressed around week 7 in the indifferent gonad, triggering testis formation. Without SRY, the default developmental pathway produces an ovary.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>SOX9 gene</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>SOX9 is activated downstream of SRY and is essential for sustaining testis development, but SRY on the Y chromosome is the initiating master switch.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>DAX1 gene</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>DAX1 is an X-linked gene involved in gonadal development. Its overexpression can antagonise SRY, but it is not the master switch for male sex determination.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the sex determination section: the SRY gene on the Y chromosome is expressed at week 7, converting the indifferent gonad into a testis."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! SRY on the Y chromosome is the master switch — its absence in XX embryos allows the default female developmental pathway."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
