          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which cells in the testes produce testosterone in response to luteinising hormon</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which cells in the testes produce testosterone in response to luteinising hormone?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sertoli cells</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Sertoli cells are the nursing cells of the seminiferous tubules. They respond to FSH (not LH) and secrete inhibin, which selectively suppresses FSH.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Spermatogonia</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Spermatogonia are diploid germ cells that give rise to mature sperm through mitosis and meiosis. They do not produce hormones.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Leydig cells</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The interstitial cells of Leydig synthesise testosterone from cholesterol in response to LH from the anterior pituitary. High local testosterone is essential for every stage of spermatogenesis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Myoid cells</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Peritubular myoid cells surround the seminiferous tubules and assist sperm transport through rhythmic contractions, but they do not produce testosterone.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Recall the two key testicular cell types: Sertoli cells respond to FSH and nurture developing sperm; Leydig cells respond to LH and produce testosterone."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. LH drives the Leydig cells to produce testosterone — remember the pairing: LH → Leydig → testosterone; FSH → Sertoli → inhibin."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
                "enableSolutionsButton": true,
