          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>What hormonal event triggers ovulation around day 14 of the menstrual cycle?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>What hormonal event triggers ovulation around day 14 of the menstrual cycle?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>A fall in progesterone levels</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Falling progesterone triggers menstrual shedding at the end of the cycle (day 26–28), not ovulation. Progesterone is produced by the corpus luteum only after ovulation has occurred.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>A surge in luteinising hormone</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Rising oestrogen from the dominant Graafian follicle triggers a mid-cycle LH surge via positive feedback on the anterior pituitary. This surge ruptures the follicle and releases the oocyte.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>A surge in follicle-stimulating hormone</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>FSH drives follicular growth during the early follicular phase, but the ovulatory trigger is specifically the LH surge, not an FSH surge.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>A rise in anti-Müllerian hormone</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>AMH reflects the ovarian follicular reserve and is used clinically to assess fertility potential, but it plays no role in triggering ovulation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the ovarian cycle: rising oestrogen from the dominant Graafian follicle triggers a mid-cycle LH surge that ruptures the follicle, causing ovulation."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The LH surge — triggered by positive feedback from rising oestrogen — is the key signal that ruptures the Graafian follicle."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
                "enableSolutionsButton": true,
                "enableCheckButton": true,
                "type": "auto",
