          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>What is the primary mechanism by which the combined oral contraceptive pill prev</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>What is the primary mechanism by which the combined oral contraceptive pill prevents pregnancy?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Spermicidal action within the uterine cavity</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The COCP has no spermicidal properties. It does thicken cervical mucus as a secondary mechanism, but this impedes sperm transport rather than killing sperm.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Suppression of ovulation via negative feedback on the HPG axis</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The synthetic oestrogen and progestogen in the COCP maintain constant negative feedback on the hypothalamus and pituitary, suppressing GnRH, FSH, and LH — preventing follicular maturation and ovulation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Destruction of the released ovum by synthetic hormones</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The COCP does not destroy ova. It prevents their release in the first place by suppressing the hormonal signals required for follicular maturation and ovulation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Premature degeneration of the corpus luteum</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The COCP prevents ovulation entirely, so no corpus luteum forms in the first place. Corpus luteum degeneration is a normal event at the end of non-pregnant cycles, not a contraceptive mechanism.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the contraception section: the COCP's primary mechanism is suppressing GnRH, FSH, and LH through constant negative feedback, thereby preventing ovulation."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. The COCP suppresses the HPG axis, preventing follicular development and ovulation — with additional secondary effects on cervical mucus and the endometrium."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
                "enableSolutionsButton": true,
                "enableCheckButton": true,
