          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which hormone rises sharply at menopause and serves as the most reliable hormona</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which hormone rises sharply at menopause and serves as the most reliable hormonal marker for confirming it?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Oestrone</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Oestrone becomes the predominant oestrogen after menopause (from peripheral conversion of adrenal androgens in adipose tissue), but its levels do not rise sharply — it replaces oestradiol at overall lower levels.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Progesterone</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Progesterone falls at menopause because ovulation ceases and no corpus luteum forms. It does not rise.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Inhibin</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Inhibin is produced by ovarian granulosa cells and falls at menopause as follicular function ceases. Its decline actually contributes to the rise in FSH by removing negative feedback.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Follicle-stimulating hormone</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. With depleted ovarian follicles, oestrogen and inhibin levels fall. Without their negative feedback, the anterior pituitary markedly increases FSH secretion. FSH above 30 IU/L is the most reliable hormonal marker of menopause.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the menopause section: with ovarian follicular depletion, oestrogen and inhibin fall, removing negative feedback and causing FSH to rise above 30 IU/L."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! FSH rises sharply because the failing ovaries no longer produce enough oestrogen and inhibin to maintain negative feedback on the pituitary."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
